data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code is the **timeout enforcement** pattern — it uses `Thread.Abort()` to kill a thread that exceeds a time limit and `Thread.ResetAbort()` to swallow the abort inside the worker. Both APIs throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8.

### What's broken in .NET 8

| API | .NET 8 behavior |
|-----|-----------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never triggered — the exception type still exists but is never thrown |

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate MUST check the CancellationToken to be stoppable.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run schedules on the thread pool — no manual Thread needed
            Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

            // .GetAwaiter().GetResult() unwraps AggregateException to the inner exception
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Callers must change too

The fundamental shift is from **preemptive** (runtime kills the thread) to **cooperative** (work must voluntarily check for cancellation). Your `Func<T>` becomes `Func<CancellationToken, T>`:

```csharp
// ❌ Old — work doesn't need to know about cancellation
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => ComputeExpensiveResult(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ✅ New — work must check the token at regular checkpoints
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();  // cooperative checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Accepting `Func<T>` without a token** | Cancellation has zero effect — the work runs to completion regardless of timeout. The token must reach the work. |
| **No checkpoints in long-running work** | `ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` only works when called. A 10-minute CPU loop with no checkpoint is unstoppable. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always `using` or `finally`-dispose it. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Blocking I/O that ignores the token** | Sync calls like `socket.Read()` won't respond to cancellation. Use async overloads (`ReadAsync(buffer, ct)`) or `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne()` for sleeps. |

### If the work truly can't cooperate

If you're calling unmodifiable code (e.g., a third-party library with no `CancellationToken` support), move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` — that's the only safe way to forcibly stop uncooperative code in modern .NET. `Thread.Abort` has no replacement for the preemptive case.
